*gnaws another enemy kneecap to shreds*<BR>Veloxia@hotmail.com</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uimogenelddar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ImogenElddar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:43:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> loot dogma</span><hr size=1> Human nature being what it is, I can assure you of a few things:<br>
<br>
1) Just about any system you can possibly image, somebody uses, another person advocates passionately, and somebody else despises.<br>
<br>
2) There are almost as many systems as there are players, and though many of them are so similar as to be nearly indistinguishable to you or I, the proponents of each system will insist that the differences are crucial.<br>
<br>
3) Everybody insists that their system is &quot;more fair&quot; than every other system.<br>
<br>
4) People spend a lot of time arguing over which system is best, and tend to get quite angry when you don't agree with them.<br>
<br>
5) The arguments tend to devolve into personal attacks, usually along the lines of, &quot;You don't like my system because you're selfish and you want a system that gives your class an unfair advantage!&quot;<br>
<br>
6) As of yet, nobody has actually produced any concrete evidence that their system is, in the long run, any better or more fair than pure randomness.<br>
<br>
7) It's rather like religion, when you get right down to it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugenththetiger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Genth the Tiger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 3:55:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: loot dogma</span><hr size=1> what i find works best.<br>
1. Have a master looter<br>
2. When someone leaves everyone rolls 1-100.<br>
3. Their number determines the order in which they pick an item from what was recieved in loot. <br>
4. repeat if everyone gets and item and more loot is left. <br>
<br>
This works great for camps where there are lots of drops like Velks village etc.  and with this server being all NO DROP i'd think it would be ideal for any camp really. <br>
<br>
Genth <br>
Khala Dun of the 38th rank <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugenththetiger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Genth the Tiger</A> at: 2/6/02 12:56:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubraellarth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Braellarth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/6/02 5:03:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1286.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: loot dogma</span><hr size=1> There are flaws in each system, doesnt make them bad.. but makes some rules better situational.<br>
<br>
NBG - need before greed. only problem is that certain spots have no items for xxx class, or are set up specifically for one class only. Take Drolvag captain. Mostly warrior items... so you have to draw the line when you create the group or invite new people.. NBG in drolvag captain is on the verge of selfishness and explotiation of other class's.<br>
Do you make a rule like: warriors nbg on the cobolt (warrior kunark class armour) and jade mace free for all, cloak ffa (cloak is'nt that great and it's so common everyone gets one after there first hunt in this spot)<br>
<br>
Defining rules and inform people if you know what 'might' drop, so that they know what they are getting into, if you dont know and no one in group knows.. Nbg is good but evaluate what you get at the end of a night, as a puller and tank i put my life on the line a lot more than some of the other classes, risking my life on extreemly dangerouse splitting, then tanking or agro mangement.. sometimes i will end up with nothing from the night, i dont mind Ngb at all.. but sometimes i get royally screwed over, since i have melee and magic.. often items goto the 'pure' prime class before hybrids, so i have been completely screwed with Nbg before... a fair group and nbg is perfect, but dont go useing it as a means of exploitation, earns you a worse reputation imho! (greed to the extreem)<br>
<br>
Port/split - great, but i have had evacers ld, come back then port without me, or hold items for me while i am pulling/splitting and not give them back.. had the same person litteraly take around 5 quest gems for veliouse armour that way.. but everyone says 'she's a great druid!' so rather than complain i stick up with it.. happens again. Now this is a occurence with one person i had on my last server... but it scares me when i do this with people i dont know, i have a fear of evacers looting now.. only use this with people you trust, it can be mis-used and people can get away with it.<br>
